Shaw Communications Inc. launches Comcast's X1 TV platform to wrestle back market share from Telus
Shaw is hoping that the new TV product will help bring cord cutters, cord shavers and cord nevers back into the cable system 




Canadian Press 










Emily Jackson 
 

January 11, 20174:15 PM EST 
Filed underFP Tech Desk 

Comment


Facebook


Twitter


Email


More







Share this storyShaw Communications Inc. launches Comcast's X1 TV platform to wrestle back market share from TelusTumblrPinterestGoogle PlusLinkedInReddit 








Shaw Communications Inc. has launched a long-awaited, majorly upgraded television product that it expects will take on Internet-protocol TV offerings from its main competitor.
Called Shaw BlueSky TV, the new product uses Comcast’s X1 platform and is now available to Calgary customers, the Western Canadian cable company announced Wednesday, the day before it reports results for the first quarter of 2017 and holds its annual general meeting.
Shaw is pitching the new service, which it plans to launch in other markets in the coming months, as a “best-in-class” premium TV product that comes with a voice-controlled remote and advanced search functions.
“We are proud to be the first in Canada to pioneer Comcast’s ground-breaking technology and to be their first international partner,” Shaw CEO Brad Shaw said in a statement.
But it won’t be the last television provider to turn to Comcast’s X1 platform after abandoning its internal attempts to create an IPTV in 2015 and taking a $55-million write-down in the process.
Rogers Communications Inc. announced in December it, too, inked a deal with Comcast X1, killing its own IPTV development in a move that will result in a $475-million to $525-million write-down. It will roll out the new technology in 2018.
The adoption of Comcast’s platform comes as cable companies lose subscribers to traditional telephone companies BCE Inc. in Eastern Canada and Telus Corp. in the west, stealing market share with their superior IPTV services, Fibe TV and Optic TV.
In the first nine months of 2016, Shaw and Rogers respectively lost 98,000 and 63,000 TV subscribers while Telus and Bell gained 38,000 and 7,000, respectively.
Comcast posted a net gain of 170,000 customers last year, the first time its done so in the approximately eight years since launching the platform, technology and product president Tony Werner said in a joint interview with Shaw president Jay Mehr on Wednesday.
“It’s IPTV, but it’s a lot more than that,” Werner said, adding it uses cloud-based software that allows Comcast to make changes to its offerings on the fly. The voice remote has been a “huge success” with usage expected to double in 2017, he said, and the platform can be used for Internet of Things applications such as turning up a thermostat.  
Mehr said the new TV product will help bring cord cutters, cord shavers and cord nevers back into the cable system.
“This for sure is a differentiated video product,” he said, noting the variety of applications available including Netflix.
He wouldn’t say exactly when he expects Shaw to quell subscriber losses, but said he expects it will gain traction more quickly than Comcast did.
“It won’t take us that long,” Mehr said.







